<div class="page-eyebrow">Protocol Guide</div>
<h1>How to fix<br>nutrient deficiencies &#8212;<br><em>test first, correct what&#8217;s actually low.</em></h1>
<p class="guide-hero-sub">Most nutrient deficiencies are silent &#8212; no obvious symptoms, but measurable effects on energy, immune function, cognition, and longevity biomarkers. This guide covers which deficiencies matter most, what labs to run, and how to correct them at the right dose with the right form.</p>
</section>

<div class="guide-meta">
<div class="guide-meta-item">Updated <span>May 2026</span></div>
<div class="guide-meta-item">Reading time <span>~14 min</span></div>
<div class="guide-meta-item">Affiliate <span>Disclosed</span></div>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Why nutrient status is a longevity variable</h2>
<p>Nutrient deficiencies are not just a developing-world problem. Eating a calorie-sufficient modern Western diet produces a predictable set of insufficiencies &#8212; not from starvation, but from the combination of ultra-processed foods that crowd out nutrient-dense choices, soil depletion that reduces mineral content in produce, sun avoidance and indoor lifestyles that impair vitamin D synthesis, and physiological demands that standard reference ranges were never designed to optimize for.</p>
<p>The distinction between &#8220;deficient&#8221; and &#8220;insufficient&#8221; is clinically important. Reference ranges define deficiency as the threshold at which deficiency diseases appear &#8212; rickets, pellagra, scurvy. But decades of research have identified a much wider range of insufficiency where nutrients are low enough to impair optimal function without causing classical disease. Vitamin D is the clearest example: clinical deficiency is defined as below 20 ng/mL, but longevity research consistently identifies increased disease risk below 40 ng/mL. Millions of people are told their vitamin D is &#8220;fine&#8221; at 28 ng/mL while sitting in a range associated with elevated cancer risk, worse immune function, and impaired bone metabolism.</p>
<p>The nutrient deficiencies that matter most for longevity are those with the largest footprint: they appear in large fractions of the population, affect multiple downstream biological processes, and respond clearly to correction. Vitamin D, magnesium, omega-3s, and zinc are in this category. Others &#8212; folate, B12, ferritin, selenium &#8212; matter intensely for specific populations or conditions.</p>
<div class="callout">
<div class="callout-label">The reference range problem</div>
<p>Standard lab reference ranges are set from population distributions, not from what&#8217;s optimal. A vitamin D result of 25 ng/mL may be flagged as &#8220;normal&#8221; because it&#8217;s within the middle 95% of the measured population &#8212; but if much of that population is also deficient, the range reflects a deficient population. Longevity-optimized targets are often substantially higher than what&#8217;s considered &#8220;normal&#8221; on a standard lab report.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>The seven nutrients most worth testing</h2>
<p>These are the highest-priority deficiencies to identify and correct, based on prevalence, biological impact, and response to supplementation.</p>
<div class="marker-grid">
<div class="marker-cell">
<div class="marker-cell-label">Fat-soluble vitamin</div>
<div class="marker-cell-title">Vitamin D (25-OH)</div>
<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal: <span>40&#8211;70 ng/mL</span><br>Insufficient: <span>20&#8211;39 ng/mL</span><br>Deficient: <span>&lt;20 ng/mL</span><br><br>Affects immunity, bone metabolism, testosterone, mood, and inflammation. ~40% of US adults are below 20 ng/mL.</div>
</div>
