<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal (serum): <span>80&#8211;120 &#956;g/dL</span><br>Deficient: <span>&lt;70 &#956;g/dL</span><br><br>Required for testosterone synthesis, immune function, wound healing, and DNA repair. Depleted by alcohol, sweat, and low animal protein intake.</div>
</div>
<div class="marker-cell">
<div class="marker-cell-label">B vitamin</div>
<div class="marker-cell-title">Vitamin B12</div>
<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal: <span>&gt;500 pg/mL</span><br>Concern: <span>200&#8211;400 pg/mL</span><br>Deficient: <span>&lt;200 pg/mL</span><br><br>Neurological function, methylation, DNA synthesis. Risk groups: vegans, adults 60+, metformin users.</div>
</div>
<div class="marker-cell">
<div class="marker-cell-label">Iron storage</div>
<div class="marker-cell-title">Ferritin</div>
<div class="marker-cell-ranges">Optimal (women): <span>30&#8211;100 ng/mL</span><br>Optimal (men): <span>50&#8211;150 ng/mL</span><br>Deficient: <span>&lt;12 ng/mL</span><br><br>Low ferritin causes fatigue and poor cognition even before anemia develops.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The seventh: <a href="/biomarkers/folate">folate</a>. Adequate folate status is essential for DNA synthesis, methylation, and homocysteine metabolism. Testing serum folate provides a snapshot; RBC folate reflects longer-term tissue status. Those with the MTHFR variant require methylfolate (L-5-MTHF) rather than folic acid.</p>
</div>

