<div class="content-section">
<h2>The big three: what to fix first</h2>
<h3>1. Vitamin D &#8212; the most consequential deficiency to correct</h3>
<p>Vitamin D functions less like a vitamin and more like a steroid hormone &#8212; it has receptors in virtually every tissue type and regulates hundreds of genes involved in immunity, inflammation, cell proliferation, and calcium metabolism. Its deficiency is extraordinarily common: an estimated 40% of US adults have levels below 20 ng/mL, and the majority of the remainder sit in the 20 to 39 ng/mL range that research increasingly associates with suboptimal outcomes.</p>
<p>The longevity-optimized target is 40 to 70 ng/mL of 25-hydroxyvitamin D. Getting there requires knowing your baseline, because the dose needed depends entirely on where you start. Someone at 15 ng/mL typically needs 5,000 to 8,000 IU per day for several months; someone at 32 ng/mL may reach target with 2,000 to 3,000 IU. The standard recommendation of 600 to 800 IU &#8212; the US RDA &#8212; is insufficient to move most deficient individuals into optimal range.</p>
<p>Critical co-factors: vitamin D requires magnesium for conversion to its active form, and vitamin K2 to properly route the calcium it mobilizes into bone rather than arteries. Supplementing high-dose vitamin D without adequate magnesium and K2 is the most common supplementation error. The practical protocol: test first, supplement to target, retest at 3 months, then annually.</p>

<h3>2. Magnesium &#8212; the silent deficiency nobody measures correctly</h3>
<p>Magnesium is a cofactor in over 300 enzymatic reactions, including ATP synthesis, DNA repair, protein synthesis, and neuromuscular function. Its deficiency is also among the most systematically underdiagnosed &#8212; because the standard test (serum magnesium) is nearly useless for detecting it.</p>
<p>Only about 1% of the body&#8217;s magnesium is in the blood. The body maintains serum magnesium within a narrow range by drawing from bone and muscle stores when dietary intake is inadequate &#8212; meaning serum magnesium can be &#8220;normal&#8221; while tissue stores are substantially depleted. RBC magnesium (measuring magnesium inside red blood cells) is the superior test and the one that actually reflects tissue status. The target is 5.2 to 6.5 mg/dL on an RBC magnesium test.</p>
<p>Magnesium depletion is driven by the modern diet and worsened by alcohol, diuretics, high sugar intake, chronic stress, and caffeine. The most bioavailable supplemental forms are magnesium glycinate (best tolerated, calming effect), magnesium malate (energy metabolism support), and magnesium threonate (brain-targeted). Magnesium oxide &#8212; found in most cheap supplements &#8212; has poor bioavailability and primarily acts as a laxative.</p>
<div class="warning-callout">
<div class="warning-callout-label">Zinc and copper balance</div>
<p>Zinc and copper compete for absorption. Supplementing zinc at doses above 25 to 40mg per day for extended periods can deplete copper, impairing iron metabolism, SOD activity, and cardiovascular function. If supplementing zinc for deficiency correction, ensure dietary copper is adequate (organ meats, shellfish, nuts) or include a small copper supplement (1 to 2mg/day). Test copper if supplementing zinc at therapeutic doses for more than a few months.</p>
</div>

<h3>3. Omega-3 index &#8212; the deficiency you can measure precisely</h3>
<p>Unlike most nutrient assessments, the <a href="/biomarkers/omega-3-index">omega-3 index</a> directly measures the percentage of EPA and DHA in red blood cell membranes &#8212; reflecting tissue incorporation over the past 2 to 3 months. It is the most reliable biomarker for omega-3 status, far more informative than dietary recall or the amount of fish oil you think you&#8217;re taking.</p>
<p>The evidence-backed target is an omega-3 index of 8% or higher. A 2021 analysis of the Framingham Offspring Study found that individuals in the top quartile of omega-3 index had 34% lower all-cause mortality than those in the bottom quartile. Most US adults without consistent fatty fish intake have an index of 4 to 5%. Moving from 4% to 8% typically requires 2 to 4 grams of combined EPA+DHA per day. Retest at 12 weeks to confirm response.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>B vitamins, methylation, and the homocysteine connection</h2>
<p>Vitamins B12, B6, and folate are collectively the methylation nutrients &#8212; they drive the one-carbon metabolism pathway that converts homocysteine back to methionine and cysteine. When any of the three is insufficient, homocysteine accumulates. Elevated <a href="/biomarkers/homocysteine">homocysteine</a> (above 10 &#956;mol/L) is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease, cognitive decline, and all-cause mortality &#8212; and it is almost entirely addressable with B vitamin correction.</p>
<p>The MTHFR gene variant deserves specific mention. Approximately 10% of people are homozygous for the C677T variant, which reduces the MTHFR enzyme&#8217;s efficiency by 60 to 70%, impairing folate metabolism and raising homocysteine even with adequate dietary folate. These individuals require methylated forms &#8212; methylfolate (L-5-MTHF) and methylcobalamin &#8212; rather than folic acid and cyanocobalamin, which require the impaired conversion step to become biologically active.</p>
<p>Vitamin B12 deficiency has a long latency before neurological symptoms appear, which makes it particularly dangerous &#8212; by the time neuropathy is present, damage has often been accumulating for years. The groups most at risk are vegans, adults over 60 (reduced gastric acid and intrinsic factor impair absorption), and metformin users (the drug reduces B12 absorption in a dose-dependent manner). The longevity-optimized target for serum B12 is above 500 pg/mL, not the clinical deficiency threshold of 200 pg/mL.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Ferritin: the iron deficiency that precedes anemia</h2>
<p>Iron deficiency anemia &#8212; low hemoglobin with small red blood cells &#8212; is the end stage of iron depletion. Long before anemia develops, ferritin falls as the body draws on stored iron to maintain circulating hemoglobin. Low <a href="/biomarkers/ferritin">ferritin</a> produces fatigue, brain fog, hair loss, cold intolerance, and impaired exercise capacity &#8212; attributable to insufficient iron for mitochondrial function and thyroid hormone production, not just oxygen-carrying capacity.</p>
<p>The optimal ferritin range for women is 30 to 100 ng/mL; for men, 50 to 150 ng/mL. Many women with ferritin below 20 to 30 ng/mL report significant fatigue that resolves with iron repletion, even though hemoglobin is technically normal. Iron supplementation should be confirmed with testing first &#8212; excess iron is pro-inflammatory and pro-oxidative. Ferrous bisglycinate is the best-tolerated form with the fewest gastrointestinal side effects. Vitamin C taken with iron meaningfully enhances absorption; calcium and coffee impair it.</p>
<p>One important caveat: very high ferritin (above 200 to 300 ng/mL in women, above 300 to 400 ng/mL in men) can reflect iron overload or, more commonly, inflammation &#8212; since ferritin is an acute phase reactant. High ferritin should be investigated, not supplemented.</p>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>Vitamin K2: the calcium router</h2>
<p>Vitamin K2 is one of the most undersupplied nutrients in the modern diet. Its primary role is activating vitamin K-dependent proteins &#8212; most importantly osteocalcin (which deposits calcium into bone) and matrix Gla protein (MGP, which prevents calcium deposition in arteries). Without adequate K2, calcium mobilized by vitamin D is poorly directed: it may calcify arteries while underbuilding bone &#8212; exactly the opposite of what you want.</p>
<p>This is why the combination of vitamin D and K2 supplementation has a better cardiovascular and bone safety profile than vitamin D alone. The primary dietary source of K2 (specifically MK-7, the most bioavailable form) is natto, a fermented soybean food common in Japan but rare in Western diets. Smaller amounts are found in aged hard cheeses and full-fat dairy. For most people, supplementation at 100 to 200 mcg of MK-7 per day is the practical solution. Note: those on warfarin must not alter K2 intake without medical supervision.</p>
</div>

