<div class="content-section">
<h2>Form matters: how to supplement correctly</h2>
<p>The form of a supplement determines its bioavailability. Most cheap multivitamins use forms chosen for cost rather than absorption &#8212; the difference between a supplement that works and one that doesn&#8217;t is often the form.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Magnesium:</strong> Glycinate or malate (high bioavailability, well tolerated). Avoid oxide (poor absorption, primarily laxative effect). Threonate for cognitive applications.</li>
<li><strong>Vitamin B12:</strong> Methylcobalamin or adenosylcobalamin preferred &#8212; especially for MTHFR variant carriers. Cyanocobalamin requires conversion and is less effective in some individuals.</li>
<li><strong>Folate:</strong> Methylfolate (L-5-MTHF) for anyone with MTHFR variant or uncertain status. Folic acid requires enzymatic conversion that is impaired in MTHFR variants.</li>
<li><strong>Iron:</strong> Ferrous bisglycinate is the best-tolerated form. Take with vitamin C; avoid with calcium, coffee, or antacids.</li>
<li><strong>Vitamin K2:</strong> MK-7 form has a longer half-life and lower daily dosing requirement. Requires fat in the meal for absorption (fat-soluble).</li>
<li><strong>Zinc:</strong> Zinc picolinate, glycinate, or citrate are better absorbed than zinc oxide or sulfate. Separate from calcium and iron supplements by at least 2 hours.</li>
<li><strong>Omega-3:</strong> Triglyceride form is better absorbed than ethyl ester form (common in cheaper products). Take with a fatty meal.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="content-section">
<h2>The protocol: how to sequence testing and correction</h2>
<div class="phase-card">
<div class="phase-number">01</div>
<div>
<div class="phase-title">Run the priority panel</div>
<div class="phase-desc">Order vitamin D (25-OH), RBC magnesium, omega-3 index, zinc, vitamin B12, ferritin, and homocysteine. Add folate (RBC folate preferred) if homocysteine is elevated or you have MTHFR variant. This panel tells you which deficiencies actually exist &#8212; don&#8217;t supplement blindly before this.</div>
<div class="phase-timeline">Week 0</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="phase-card">
<div class="phase-number">02</div>
<div>
<div class="phase-title">Address the big three immediately</div>
<div class="phase-desc">If vitamin D is below 40 ng/mL: begin 3,000 to 5,000 IU/day with K2 (100&#8211;200 mcg MK-7) and adequate magnesium. If omega-3 index is below 8%: begin 2 to 4g combined EPA+DHA daily. If RBC magnesium is below 5.2 mg/dL: begin magnesium glycinate 200 to 400mg/night. These three are safe to start immediately pending retest.</div>
<div class="phase-timeline">Week 1</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="phase-card">
<div class="phase-number">03</div>
<div>
<div class="phase-title">Correct B vitamin and iron deficiencies</div>
<div class="phase-desc">If B12 is below 500 pg/mL: begin methylcobalamin 1,000 mcg/day sublingually. If homocysteine is above 10 &#956;mol/L: add methylfolate (400&#8211;800 mcg/day) and B6 (25&#8211;50mg/day). If ferritin is below optimal: begin ferrous bisglycinate 25&#8211;50mg with vitamin C, taken between meals on an empty stomach.</div>
<div class="phase-timeline">Week 1&#8211;2</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="phase-card">
<div class="phase-number">04</div>
<div>
<div class="phase-title">Address zinc and K2</div>
<div class="phase-desc">If zinc is below 80 &#956;g/dL: supplement zinc picolinate or glycinate at 25&#8211;40mg/day with meals. Add 1 to 2mg copper/day if supplementing zinc for more than 4 to 6 weeks. Add vitamin K2 (100&#8211;200 mcg MK-7) if not already included with vitamin D supplementation. Take with a fat-containing meal.</div>
<div class="phase-timeline">Week 1&#8211;2</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="phase-card">
<div class="phase-number">05</div>
<div>
<div class="phase-title">Retest at 3 months</div>
<div class="phase-desc">Retest vitamin D, RBC magnesium, omega-3 index, B12, ferritin, and homocysteine. Most people need dose adjustments &#8212; especially vitamin D, which has high individual variability in response. Don&#8217;t assume a dose is working without confirming with labs. This retest is not optional if you want to know whether the correction actually worked.</div>
<div class="phase-timeline">Month 3</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="phase-card">
<div class="phase-number">06</div>
<div>
<div class="phase-title">Maintain with annual retesting</div>
<div class="phase-desc">Once optimal levels are confirmed, annual retesting maintains them over time. Vitamin D levels drift seasonally, magnesium stores can be re-depleted by stress or poor diet, and ferritin in premenopausal women requires ongoing attention. The goal is not to correct once but to maintain optimal status across decades.</div>
<div class="phase-timeline">Annually</div>
