<div class="content-section">
<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which nutrient deficiencies are most common?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Vitamin D, magnesium, and omega-3s are the three most prevalent deficiencies in adults eating a modern Western diet. Vitamin D deficiency affects an estimated 40% of US adults. Magnesium insufficiency is thought to affect up to 50% of the population. Omega-3 deficiency &#8212; an index below 8% &#8212; affects the large majority of adults who don&#8217;t regularly eat fatty fish. Zinc, B12, and folate deficiencies are also common, particularly in older adults, vegans, and people with GI conditions.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I just take a multivitamin instead of testing?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">A multivitamin is a poor substitute for testing. Most contain nutrients in forms with poor bioavailability (magnesium oxide, cyanocobalamin), at doses too low to correct established deficiencies. Someone with vitamin D at 15 ng/mL needs a fundamentally different intervention than someone at 38 ng/mL &#8212; a multivitamin provides neither. Test first so you correct what&#8217;s actually low, at the dose required, in the form that works. See the <a href="/biomarkers/vitamin-d">vitamin D biomarker page</a> for a full range breakdown.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between deficiency and insufficiency?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Clinical deficiency is the threshold at which deficiency diseases appear &#8212; rickets for vitamin D, scurvy for vitamin C. Insufficiency refers to levels below what research suggests is optimal for longevity and disease prevention, even if not low enough to cause a classic disease. For vitamin D, clinical deficiency is below 20 ng/mL, but insufficiency for longevity purposes begins below 40 ng/mL. Millions of people are told their labs are &#8220;normal&#8221; while sitting in a range associated with elevated disease risk.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does it take to correct a nutrient deficiency?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Timeline varies by nutrient. Vitamin D typically takes 3 to 6 months to normalize. Magnesium tissue stores take 3 to 6 months to replete. Ferritin takes 3 to 6 months of iron supplementation to correct. Vitamin B12 injections can replete stores in weeks; oral B12 takes several months. Omega-3 index responds within 8 to 12 weeks at adequate doses. Retesting at 3 months is the standard protocol for confirming corrections.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is it possible to take too much of a nutrient?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Yes, for fat-soluble vitamins in particular. Vitamins A, D, E, and K accumulate in fat tissue and can reach toxic levels with excessive supplementation. Vitamin D toxicity typically occurs above 10,000 IU/day for extended periods. Iron should never be supplemented without confirmed deficiency &#8212; excess iron promotes oxidative stress and inflammation. Very high-dose B6 (above 100&#8211;200mg/day for extended periods) can cause peripheral neuropathy. Water-soluble vitamins have much lower toxicity risk.</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should I test nutrients annually?</div>
<div class="faq-answer">Annual testing for vitamin D, omega-3 index, ferritin, and homocysteine is reasonable for most adults. After correcting a deficiency and confirming it at 3 months, annual retesting ensures maintenance. Vitamin D levels drift seasonally. B12 in people over 60, vegans, or metformin users warrants annual monitoring. The goal is not to correct once but to maintain optimal levels across decades &#8212; which requires periodic verification.</div>
</div>
</div>
